</P>
<P>
The LIPA plan to use fuel cells to supply the grid
is part of an effort to generate 25 percent of
the utility's energy using renewable sources by 2014, a goal
set by the New York state Public Service Commission last
year, Kessel said.
</P>
<P>
The utility has also already contracted with Florida Power and Light
to build a windmill farm -- 40 to 50 windmill
turbines -- about six miles from the Island's south shore,
near Robert Moses State Park, providing 140 megawatts of power
to the grid. Long Island's power demands averaged about 2,989
megawatts per hour in 2004 during peak hours.
</P>
<P>
But while windmills create electricity from ocean winds, the fuel cells
used for LIPA's project will use a fossil fuel to
operate: natural gas. The public service commission includes fuel cells
in its policy, a commission spokesman, David Flanagan, said, to
spur the development of cells that will one day run
on renewable resources like methane or electrical current.
</P>
<P>
Gordian Raacke, head of the environmental group Renewable Energy Long Island,
discussed the future of fuel cells at the Babylon Town
Hall news conference, where he praised LIPA's newest energy project.
</P>
<P>
Raacke powers his East End home with solar panels. Under a
LIPA plan that allows homeowners using solar energy to "run
their meters backward," Raacke feeds electricity back to the grid
and gets credits on his electric bill instead of charges.
"I don't pay anything for electricity," he said. "When the
day is overcast and I need energy, I use the
credits."
</P>
<P>
The fuel cell of the future, Raacke believes, will be able
to extract and store hydrogen from solar- and wind-generated energy,
so if he had one in his house, he would
not need to tap the grid on a cloudy day.
"Fuel cell technology provides an important link in the alternative
energy chain," he said. "It closes the loop."
</P>
<P>
Saillant of Plug Power said it is indeed possible for fuel
cells to store hydrogen gas taken from a mixture of
water and the electrical current generated by wind turbines and
solar panels. Ideally, the stored gas would be used on
a calm or overcast day to continue powering and heating
the home.
</P>
<P>
But he estimates that fuel cells not requiring natural gas are,
under the best federal-financing conditions, at least 15 years away.
</P>
<P>
For now in Mineola, Davis is happy with the first month
of fuel cell power in his home. "Having experienced a
major outage, I can really appreciate this," he said.
</P>
